		<div class="entry-content"><div class="w592"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2011/12/25/us/BORDER-slide-30VG-LN/BORDER-slide-30VG-LN-tmagArticle.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2011/12/25/us/BORDER-slide-30VG-LN/BORDER-slide-30VG-LN-tmagArticle.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2011/12/25/us/BORDER-slide-30VG-LN/BORDER-slide-30VG-LN-tmagArticle.jpg" id="100000004521668" width="592" height="395" alt="To help her students see the complexity of immigration issues, Rachelle Lamoureux uses a slide show about high school students who live in Mexico but commute across the border to go to school in the United States. &lt;a href=&quot;//www.nytimes.com/slideshow/2012/01/17/us/BORDER.html&quot;&gt;Related Slide Show&lt;/a&gt;"   /><meta itemprop="height" content="395"><meta itemprop="width" content="592"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">To help her students see the complexity of immigration issues, Rachelle Lamoureux uses a slide show about high school students who live in Mexico but commute across the border to go to school in the United States. <a href="//www.nytimes.com/slideshow/2012/01/17/us/BORDER.html">Related Slide Show</a></span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Jim Wilson/The New York Times</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="//learning.blogs.nytimes.com/2016/08/30/reader-idea-fostering-a-deeper-understanding-of-current-immigration-issues-using-infographics-and-photographs/" data-title="Reader Idea | Fostering a Deeper Understanding of Current Immigration Issues Using Infographics and Photographs" data-description="This Reader Idea asks students to take a closer look at the issue of immigration.">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Our week of <a href="//learning.blogs.nytimes.com/category/great-ideas-from-readers/">Reader Ideas</a> continues with this one, by <strong>Rachelle Lamoureux</strong>, that asks students to take a closer look at the issue of immigration. By the end of the lesson, students showed in their writing how much they were grappling with multiple viewpoints &#8212; and how Times infographics and photographs helped them feel empathy and see a complex issue in the context of history. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Have you taught with The Times? Or is it in your plans for this school year? <a href="//learning.blogs.nytimes.com/great-ideas-from-our-readers/">Tell us about it here</a>.<br />
<span id="more-170616"></span></p>
<hr/>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Teacher:</strong> Rachelle Lamoureux</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Institution:</strong> <a href="//erikramstad.minot.k12.nd.us/">Erik Ramstad Middle School</a>, Minot, N.D.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Grade Level:</strong> Seventh</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Idea:</strong> Students gain a deeper understanding of immigration issues today by analyzing two New York Times infographics and a slide show.  </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Why We Chose It:</strong> It&#8217;s one thing to tell students that the United States is a nation of immigrants, but taking another tack, as Ms. Lamoureux does here, allows them to see for themselves where people have emigrated from over the decades &#8212; and why. Over the course of this lesson, her students challenged their own beliefs about immigrants as they considered multiple aspects of the issue. </p>
<hr/>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>What Ms. Lamoureux Did and Why, in Her Own Words</strong> </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Immigration is a topic that brings many opinions to a classroom discussion &#8212; even in my seventh-grade World Geography class. There is a big difference between knowing the definition of <em>immigrant</em> and understanding the personal experiences of an immigrant. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Initially, I expected student discussions to be biased. I was right; many students had their own ideas about immigrants, especially those from Mexico. There seemed to be a consensus that all Hispanics are in our country illegally and do not contribute to our economy, to our culture, and so on. Keep in mind these students are 12 years old. I promised them that I would share lots of ideas with them and that our learning and understanding about immigration might change and ultimately evolve into a deeper understanding.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">I shared two of my favorite New York Times infographics. The first was &#8220;<a href="//www.nytimes.com/interactive/2009/04/07/us/20090407-immigration-occupation.html">Immigration and Jobs: Where U.S. Workers Come From</a>.&#8221; My reason was twofold. I wanted students to see that immigrants come to the United States from all over the world. Second, I wanted them to visualize the type of jobs that many immigrants from Mexico have. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">That brought a new level of learning to the discussion. My students were able to make the connection between job opportunities in the United States and why many people move here. I took this opportunity to introduce a new perspective. I wanted my students to understand that the United States accepts that migrant workers come here to earn money, especially along the border with Mexico. I also led a brainstorm session on the reasons immigrants from Mexico might choose to work in the United States and not in Mexico. We discussed the benefits that migrant workers have in both countries. </p>
<div class="w480"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2010/04/26/learning/ImmigrationExplorer-LN/ImmigrationExplorer-LN-blog480-v2.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2010/04/26/learning/ImmigrationExplorer-LN/ImmigrationExplorer-LN-blog480-v2.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2010/04/26/learning/ImmigrationExplorer-LN/ImmigrationExplorer-LN-blog480-v2.jpg" id="100000004521656" width="480" height="300" alt="&lt;a href=&quot;//www.nytimes.com/interactive/2009/03/10/us/20090310-immigration-explorer.html&quot;&gt;Related Infographic&lt;/a&gt;"   /><meta itemprop="height" content="300"><meta itemprop="width" content="480"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text"><a href="//www.nytimes.com/interactive/2009/03/10/us/20090310-immigration-explorer.html">Related Infographic</a></span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> </span></figcaption></figure></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The second infographic I shared with students is &#8220;<a href="//www.nytimes.com/interactive/2009/03/10/us/20090310-immigration-explorer.html">Immigration Explorer</a>,&#8221; an interactive map showing settlement patterns by country of origin and over time. What I like best about this map is that it starts in 1880 and continues through 2000. I wanted my students to understand that immigration from Mexico to the United States did not start this year, or even in the past few years. Migration to our country is what made the United States what it is today. Students really liked this interactive, and I was elated that it elicited other connections as well (for example, why the 1930s had very little migration). </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">After two days of lively and sometimes even argumentative discussions, I wanted students to think deeply about what life might be like living in Mexico, why people from Mexico immigrate here, why some people come here illegally, and why our nation is having difficulties in making decisions about immigration. My students were not in agreement, but most expressed their understanding of those reasons and even felt empathy. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">To bring closure to our learning, I searched the archives of <a href="//learning.blogs.nytimes.com/">The Learning Network</a> and I found the perfect resource: the slide show &#8220;<a href="//www.nytimes.com/slideshow/2012/01/17/us/BORDER.html">An Education: Over the Border and Under the Radar</a>.&#8221; We viewed each of the eight slides. I initially thought that we would just share our thoughts together. However, my students were completely silent after the slide show was finished, and I decided, in a split second, that I would have them write instead. I gave them five minutes and asked them to simply âreactâ to what they learned. Wow, was it powerful. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Some students wrote an entire page and had adjectives galore: <em>shocking, sad, scary</em> and so on. Even my students who generally say they do not like to write and my super quiet students had lots to say in their reactions. I was so blown away by their compassion and their reactions. This was a huge success and an enduring learning experience.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Below are sample writings and reactions from my students.</p>
<div class="w480"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2016/07/10/learning/201607101LN/201607101LN-blog480.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2016/07/10/learning/201607101LN/201607101LN-blog480.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2016/07/10/learning/201607101LN/201607101LN-blog480.jpg" id="100000004522075" width="480" height="449" alt="Rachelle Lamoureuxâs students grappled with issues related to immigration, as shown here."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="449"><meta itemprop="width" content="480"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">Rachelle Lamoureuxâs students grappled with issues related to immigration, as shown here.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> </span></figcaption></figure></div>
<div class="w480"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2016/07/11/learning/20160711b/20160711b-blog480.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2016/07/11/learning/20160711b/20160711b-blog480.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2016/07/11/learning/20160711b/20160711b-blog480.jpg" id="100000004523669" width="480" height="385" alt="Another example of Rachelle Lamoureuxâs studentsâ work."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="385"><meta itemprop="width" content="480"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">Another example of Rachelle Lamoureuxâs studentsâ work.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> </span></figcaption></figure></div>
<div class="w480"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2016/07/11/learning/20170711cLN/20170711cLN-blog480.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2016/07/11/learning/20170711cLN/20170711cLN-blog480.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2016/07/11/learning/20170711cLN/20170711cLN-blog480.jpg" id="100000004523718" width="480" height="456" alt="As in many other pieces of student writing, this studentâs reaction shows consideration for multiple aspects of the immigration issue."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="456"><meta itemprop="width" content="480"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">As in many other pieces of student writing, this studentâs reaction shows consideration for multiple aspects of the immigration issue.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> </span></figcaption></figure></div>
